"script": "A woman was attacked outside her apartment while dozens of neighbors heard her screaming. Lights flicked on. People peered through their curtains. But not one of them called for help, each assuming someone else already had. And this terrible logic let the attack drag on for over half an hour. You see, the more people who witness an emergency, the less likely any single person acts. Psychologists call it the bystander effect, and they named it after that very night. It means in a crowd, you can be surrounded by people and still be completely, fatally alone.",
